00:05:44.239 --> 00:05:51.000
And now that you have a community and the community is strong and healthy, that the community is pulling the change.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:54.040
The community wants the change to happen.

00:05:54.040 --> 00:06:00.920
And I wanted to talk a little bit about the challenges that you faced with the transition and what the transition is.

00:06:00.920 --> 00:06:05.200
The transition is closed source to open source.

00:06:05.200 --> 00:06:09.320
And one of the challenges that you had mentioned to me was a leadership challenge.

00:06:09.359 --> 00:06:16.480
Like do leaders who are non-technical people, who are not embedded in the open source world,

00:06:16.480 --> 00:06:20.320
know what they are committing to when they say we are going to be open source?

00:06:20.320 --> 00:06:22.440
Could you talk a little bit about that?

00:06:22.440 --> 00:06:26.320
Thanks. That's also a question very close to my heart.

00:06:26.320 --> 00:06:30.480
You know, like my a little bit like reflection on my own background.

00:06:30.480 --> 00:06:37.720
I was trained as a statistician, finished my PhD and then jumped into a very typical clinical trial statistician role

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:41.079
and then found my way through the organization.

00:06:41.079 --> 00:06:47.000
I was really not really into the world of coding details.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:49.640
Right. I could code to save my life. Sure. Right.

00:06:49.640 --> 00:06:54.559
I mean, we all did our PhDs in using R and that's OK.

00:06:54.559 --> 00:07:01.040
But what really that meant in the open source sense, I think it has been a discovery on my part as well.

00:07:01.040 --> 00:07:06.000
And as I began to discover the world, how connected it is, like how supportive it is.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:11.079
It comes with a commitment of give and take. It talks about reproducibility.

00:07:11.079 --> 00:07:17.920
And then you begin to realize, I'm not so sure if everybody understands open source in the same way.

00:07:17.920 --> 00:07:20.119
And then this is something to learn by itself.

00:07:20.119 --> 00:07:23.320
So we started having more conversations with our leadership, of course.

00:07:23.320 --> 00:07:29.920
Right. So I had the intent from the leadership to say we want to move to R slash open source.

00:07:29.920 --> 00:07:36.279
And it took a while to explain that R slash open source is not really exactly slash topic.

00:07:36.279 --> 00:07:43.000
One thing is to say I want to move a programming language away, which means you're recreating or creating new tools.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:50.079
But on the other end, open source comes with a whole bunch of other philosophical angles, I would almost argue.

00:07:50.079 --> 00:07:56.440
What I think is that once we started explaining these details and introducing what open source communities look like

00:07:56.440 --> 00:08:01.839
and what can you achieve, how quickly problem solving, for example,

00:08:01.839 --> 00:08:07.440
are coming together as a community to realize some of the key problem areas and come up with solutions together,

00:08:07.440 --> 00:08:12.160
which then also get adopted quicker across the board, create this buy in.

00:08:12.160 --> 00:08:17.279
The leaders begin to realize that it's a huge advantage and a positive thing.

00:08:17.279 --> 00:08:24.239
So that's one conversation. And the other aspect of the conversation was we don't want to be just takers.

00:08:24.239 --> 00:08:28.200
We always want to give back. So this conversation around, oh,

00:08:28.200 --> 00:08:32.679
we have created a new code base or a new tool or a new template and now make it open source.

00:08:32.679 --> 00:08:37.599
And people will be like, do we need to invest a resource? And kind of, yeah, because you signed up for it.

00:08:37.599 --> 00:08:41.799
So it's easy to say we want to move to open source.

00:08:41.799 --> 00:08:46.280
But if you don't really walk the talk, then that might be a challenge.

00:08:46.280 --> 00:08:50.239
So I'm happy to report that this conversation goes very well these days.

00:08:50.239 --> 00:08:56.559
I think I'm having to fight less and less. Yeah, it's all good.

00:08:56.559 --> 00:09:02.280
Less and less. I remember you saying open source is tough because it's inherently anti-capitalist.

00:09:02.280 --> 00:09:07.520
