00:10:03.679 --> 00:10:09.000
I'm going to turn on one more poll here.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:16.599
That is, does your, if your company does utilize open source technology, do they give back?

00:10:16.599 --> 00:10:19.400
Because I know some will, like Eric Nance is going to say yes, right?

00:10:19.400 --> 00:10:26.159
Like pharma versus we give back. There's a lot in pharma that do, but I know that I feel like most people in other industries don't.

00:10:26.159 --> 00:10:31.440
So let's let that poll run and hop over to Slido for questions which are piling up.

00:10:31.479 --> 00:10:41.520
Okay, maybe just one small addition, Libby, to asking for Rachel's help in community building, because I'm a big fan of her in this regard.

00:10:41.520 --> 00:10:50.880
You know, like some of the details of, she shared and Rachel's here, so maybe she can jump in and if she remembers what she told us a year and a half back,

00:10:50.880 --> 00:11:00.799
one of the things she said is it's very important to think about the psychology of a person coming in to ask you a question and how you name your meetings, for example.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:12.479
So, you know, a meeting, we have decided to call our internal meetings Big In R, so Beginner Office Hours, but Bigger Big In R.

00:11:12.479 --> 00:11:23.919
And I think by naming it this way, you immediately translate to your audience that it is completely till to be a beginner, you don't know anything, all questions are good.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:35.200
And I didn't really recognize, like, this little tidbit suggestions and what kind of impact it can therefore have in building community, the community gave feedback on it later on, right?

00:11:35.200 --> 00:11:49.760
What makes them feel at home and part of it was how the meeting was set up with the very name, setting a different type of expectation that you don't need to be afraid to ask, like, questions they think is naive or stupid, it's all fine.

00:11:50.719 --> 00:12:09.119
Just again, a shout out here to really think this through on what you do with your community and also, like, take feedback from the community to understand how they are feeling when they approach the organizers of this community and what kind of space they have created. It's really helpful.

00:12:09.679 --> 00:12:24.719
Thank you so much, Judy. I love getting to hear those lessons through you, but I also have to give a shout out to the community at John Deere, because that's where I actually learned that about the beginner office hours.

00:12:24.719 --> 00:12:33.599
And I remember their team telling me that just by changing the name, I think they had double the amount of people who showed up for that community event.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:49.200
And I'm just going to share, this is a bit of an older resource now, but if it is helpful for anyone, I had tried to collect a lot of community building tips and tricks from people and put it into this Cordo site here.

00:12:49.200 --> 00:12:55.200
So, definitely check that out, but also let me know if there's other things that you want to add to that.

00:12:55.200 --> 00:13:25.119
But, yeah, Judy, the way you just said that, too, about letting people know what to expect when they come to an event, I always think of it as, like, you're hosting a party at your house and you wouldn't want somebody to just show up and you don't welcome them or take their coat or show them around, show them where they can go grab a drink or food and kind of just, like, putting ourselves into a fake physical world and imagining that community event, if it's virtual, as a party.

00:13:26.159 --> 00:13:43.119
Yeah, and thank you. I mean, with that tidbits of learnings that you shared, and you see how this gets multiplied across, right, when you tell us something, immediately, this has started happening in four countries around the world.

00:13:43.119 --> 00:13:59.520
And the user, it's a global community, but it's also regional communities with different people alternating and taking, raising their hands and leading that, and then they bring their own flavor to it. So, it's a really, like, community-driven-led piece.

00:13:59.520 --> 00:14:24.479
And I'm so happy to see that. It's, like, it takes less and less intervention from leadership side, from my side, to do this, do that. It's, like, they're running their own show. We sometimes have conversations to kind of take into account how it's going, something that we can do to make it even easier. And that's really about it. So, it took, like, one year or roughly so to get it all up and running and in a stable state.

00:14:24.479 --> 00:14:53.919
I think that's a great thing to call out is the time horizon, because a lot of people are like, we're going to make a community. It's going to be thriving on day two, right? No, you're looking at, like, 12 to 18 months of time horizon for things to kind of get going and to see the benefit. And during that 12 to 18 months, you are pumping a lot of time and effort into making things good. All right. Well, I want to hop over to the Slido and ask Marlene to unmute and ask her question. Rachel will help Marlene get unmuted.

