00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:47.919
Okay. So, my question is about your prior experience trying to promote open source in your current role. Is this the first time you've done that? Or have you had lots of experiences doing it? And maybe they weren't as successful or successful in different ways, right? I feel like success isn't necessarily one dimensional. So, I'm just curious about your experience having the lobby for that.

00:15:48.880 --> 00:15:53.760
Good question. So, you know, like my background, I mentioned I was a trained statistician.

00:15:54.719 --> 00:16:11.840
And in between, what I was doing is driving statistical methodology in the company. So, in my world, it was always peer reviewed. It was always open source share, because that's methodology is only thriving as many people adopt it.

00:16:12.559 --> 00:16:32.719
So, if you publish a paper, and no one reads it, or comments on it, or have any use of it, I would ask, like, what uses that paper exactly? So, in my world, that was always part of the deal. You reach out to the community and say, I wrote something, feedbacks on that. Please. Have you tried implementing it? Here's some code. So, this was happening anyway for a while.

00:16:33.679 --> 00:16:51.119
And then I got this mandate to say, the organization wants to move from SaaS to open source and beyond. And then that was the first time I kind of felt like I fell from a lake to ocean type of a thing. I'm like, what do I know about coding communities?

00:16:52.080 --> 00:17:09.199
And that has been also a growing journey for me to realize how amazing, intensely vast and cool this community is, right? There have been so many aspects that I've discovered on the way, and that has served as sort of like an upscaling opportunity for me.

00:17:09.199 --> 00:17:24.479
But also, then, to bring some of these notions that I observed as a statistical researcher back into this transformation piece, which means that we always shared code otherwise while writing publications. Why can't we do it?

00:17:25.199 --> 00:17:37.040
As part of Farmiverse, for example, right? If you're taking something, you can always give back and enable the rest of the community to implement some of it. But that was my experience.

