00:18:03.920 --> 00:18:16.319
So my question for you is, what does data science look like at your company? I don't want to try to pronounce that either. And how does it serve the org's internal and external missions?

00:18:18.880 --> 00:18:25.680
All right, I'm going to repeat that. What does data science look like at Boehringer? And how does it serve the org's internal and external mission?

00:18:26.160 --> 00:18:50.160
Thank you for that question. So data science is really broad, right? It can basically mean everything and nothing. Within a huge pharma company, which believe it, Boehringer is, we are not publicly traded. So many people are not aware of what we do, but we are one of the top 20 largest pharma companies in the world.

00:18:50.719 --> 00:19:10.400
It's also the largest family owned pharma company. And so that's a little bit of background in the portfolio of Boehringer. I have seen in the past 5 years or so, a heavy emphasis on data driven decision making and acceleration of timelines of drug development, right?

00:19:11.359 --> 00:19:19.359
These are common slogans you will probably hear across many other companies, but Boehringer began to think about what does that actually mean?

00:19:19.359 --> 00:19:28.880
In order to implement data driven decision making, you need the infrastructure, you need governance, you need availability of tools and templates at your fingertips.

00:19:28.880 --> 00:19:40.880
You need basically a way to extract insights rather quickly from the raw data until the formulated story that you can tell with it. So all of these kind of open areas to develop.

00:19:40.880 --> 00:19:54.319
And then what the company did was focus on building these capabilities and partially 2 years ago, I started leading 1 of these capabilities, which was called analysis and visualization. If you think about it from a.

00:19:54.400 --> 00:20:04.880
Pharma companies perspective, it's like the entire range of things you could do. Yeah, you do visualize, but you also analyze, you help reporting, you help them decision making therefore.

00:20:04.880 --> 00:20:19.760
So, the importance of data science coming into the statisticians or coders have been steadily on the rise because people realize that what amazing talents these people are and what can they enable their for at scale.

00:20:19.920 --> 00:20:45.199
And I think that's what I would say. The biggest change has been in my observation. Like, we used to have cool implementations before, but they used to be more like, oh, it's a pilot here. A pilot there, the impact was limited, but then this company really started thinking about or enabling us to think about implementation at scale. What does that mean? Right? I don't want a pilot. I want all trials.

00:20:45.199 --> 00:20:55.760
Clinical trials that are running across the board to take advantage of some of these tools and templates and that takes a lot more than, oh, yeah, have some people who know how to write code.

00:20:55.760 --> 00:21:13.760
And this is where also the open source community becomes so valuable because you realize if you want to create your universe from ground up in a silo by yourself, it takes a heck a lot of time kind of makes sense why some of these product would take 10 years to develop.

00:21:13.839 --> 00:21:25.920
But if it's open source, we have a different opportunity. We can come together as a community, decide that this is a priority across the board and try to create something together.

00:21:25.920 --> 00:21:42.800
So I think that's really one of the ways I had explained to my leadership. What's the benefit of leaning into it? Right? Everybody wins kind of in this situation. It's like, you don't have to do things that you don't find useful, but you can also contribute to it.

00:21:42.880 --> 00:21:46.160
And if they find it useful too, then you have a win-win situation.

