00:23:18.160 --> 00:23:25.119
You know, 1 of the undeniable truth about working in a company, or in the industry is that.

00:23:25.119 --> 00:23:36.640
And then everybody's like, you go ahead and do it, right? It's usually comes with that added burden of explaining to the company and how is learning pottery will help the company's bottom line.

00:23:36.640 --> 00:23:41.680
And I think this is also the same approach we have taken. We try to really understand.

00:23:41.680 --> 00:23:45.040
Is there value for the company to do it?

00:23:45.040 --> 00:24:03.760
So, 1 of the group of people that we have worked very closely are these study physicians or operations guys. They're, they're clinicians, but they're basically primary job is to, you know, understand what is the value of what we're doing and what is the value of what we're doing for the company.

00:24:33.760 --> 00:24:40.640
If you are tasked with, oh, here is this, like, 50,000 rows Excel sheet and good luck with that.

00:24:40.640 --> 00:24:46.319
That's a burden, like, people do it with all the diligence in the world.

00:24:46.319 --> 00:24:58.400
But they also realize that this is extremely tedious activity, which obviously no pharma company can avoid because it's very important to make sure that the patients are safe while taking this experimental drugs, right?

00:24:58.800 --> 00:25:01.839
This is where we could come in and we did.

00:25:01.839 --> 00:25:05.359
To create a shiny application.

00:25:05.359 --> 00:25:18.719
Where initially, when we presented, they said, oh, this is really cool. It helps us explore the data. But, you know, what I do, I also need to write down notes next to a patient record.

00:25:19.680 --> 00:25:32.959
This is what a safety physicians are meant to do. They write down notes. If they have some findings, they, they don't want to, like, forget about it. So, next time when they come back to the same file, maybe now another 10,000 rows have been added.

00:25:32.959 --> 00:25:38.560
They don't want to forget the remaining 20,000 that they have already reviewed.

00:25:38.560 --> 00:25:50.000
And that was a challenge because shiny by itself was not meant to, uh, you know, include data and information as we go, but we have an internal team of software developers.

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:55.599
Um, and I can talk about the team in a bit because I think it was really cool thing that we have it.

00:25:55.599 --> 00:26:04.719
And these guys basically took it from there and now they have enabled a shiny dashboard possibility, which has data tracking and review.

00:26:05.199 --> 00:26:09.520
And now it fits the needs, right? And immediately you see that. Oh, totally.

00:26:10.479 --> 00:26:18.479
This is now built for my personal use case. I can see the value in it and also makes my life easy. So that's like 1 example of.

00:26:19.520 --> 00:26:24.560
Motivating people and just to draw the connection back to our own communities.

00:26:24.560 --> 00:26:30.640
It has impact now. These people are community are also then involved in different projects and trials.

00:26:31.280 --> 00:26:38.239
And now they are stakeholders who know of this development are saying, oh, that's very cool. I would like to have it. Can you make it happen?

00:26:39.040 --> 00:26:46.400
Create now they have an added incentive to say, oh, I would like to lean into this and see if I can learn it and deliver it to my team.

00:26:46.959 --> 00:26:58.640
So it's kind of like works in this cyclical fashion, right? But it starts with understanding the needs of the users or the stakeholders and then really driving that point home by delivering the product, which helps.

00:26:59.280 --> 00:27:04.000
Yeah, and I wanted to call Renato in Renato if you are available to unmute.

00:27:05.359 --> 00:27:07.439
Just to chime in with a little bit of his experience.

00:27:08.959 --> 00:27:12.479
From a community perspective. Yeah, sure thing. Can you hear me?

00:27:14.400 --> 00:27:23.439
Well, yeah, so I get hired by the UN to teach macroeconomic data management with our.

00:27:23.439 --> 00:27:37.920
To central banks or central bank analysts, and I've noticed like I've done this with a few countries, and I noticed that when the director says, oh, this is really great. This is the way we're moving forward.

00:27:37.920 --> 00:27:49.040
You know, like, drop your Excel files, your random stuff, and this is the way we're moving forward. Then then what I teach sticks, right?

00:27:49.839 --> 00:27:53.439
Otherwise, it just kind of fizzles into oblivion.

00:27:53.439 --> 00:28:02.880
And like I get an email from someone, you know, like, where was that that module that you taught us or something like that in a few years?

00:28:02.880 --> 00:28:09.439
But but you can see that they still use their own their Excel files and their like old methods.

00:28:10.319 --> 00:28:23.439
And yeah, so like getting a champion, like in a managerial position to sort of mandate that that you will do reproducible science from now on is the way to go.

00:28:23.439 --> 00:28:29.040
I think thank you for that. I totally agree. I think we have that also internally.

00:28:30.160 --> 00:28:36.319
But what I can say is the internal mandate was very abstract and broad in nature, right?

00:28:36.319 --> 00:28:43.439
So the sentence that we had was we are going to move to R and open source by 2027.

00:28:44.239 --> 00:28:48.319
It's cool that it's at a timeline and it has that abstract broadness to it.

00:28:48.319 --> 00:28:54.079
But then the job of the team was to really interpret what does that even mean?

00:28:55.280 --> 00:29:02.239
Practically speaking, and then that ballooned into this massive initiative, which spans so many different aspects.

00:29:03.040 --> 00:29:07.920
And then that's that's why maybe I kind of mentioned like the organizational transformation.

00:29:07.920 --> 00:29:10.880
I really didn't mean teaching people how to code in R.

00:29:11.839 --> 00:29:15.359
It's so much beyond, like, I can give an example.

00:29:15.920 --> 00:29:24.400
So we started talking about using interactive dashboards to present data stories to our senior stakeholders, right?

00:29:24.400 --> 00:29:30.079
These are the guys who are essentially yes or no decision makers, whether to fund a trial and an asset development.

00:29:31.040 --> 00:29:35.599
Everybody was on board in the first place to say, oh, yeah, this is definitely a better way of doing it.

00:29:35.599 --> 00:29:38.400
And then came the question, well, is this validated?

00:29:41.520 --> 00:29:45.280
Well, guess what? We don't even know what is the definition of a Shiny validated.

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:49.439
So these are like practical challenges.

00:29:49.439 --> 00:29:54.719
And sometimes we just take a step back, innovate on that part first.

00:29:54.719 --> 00:29:59.839
So what we did was have a work stream started focused on validation.

00:30:00.079 --> 00:30:01.199
What do we mean, right?

00:30:01.920 --> 00:30:08.319
Even if you're creating a single use program, if you're creating an interactive Shiny, what does that mean?

00:30:08.319 --> 00:30:10.400
So how you define validation?

00:30:10.400 --> 00:30:13.439
Can you operationalize that definition?

00:30:13.439 --> 00:30:14.880
Have you updated your processes?

00:30:14.880 --> 00:30:16.560
Have you communicated to your stakeholders?

00:30:16.560 --> 00:30:24.239
And that became this whole square as sort of like, I see that as one of the fundamental pillars that any organization need to think through.

00:30:24.239 --> 00:30:26.959
Because these are the questions you will have from your stakeholders, right?

00:30:26.959 --> 00:30:33.760
If your stakeholders and your leadership is used to this idea of validated outputs, it translates to something.

00:30:33.760 --> 00:30:36.800
And then you cannot just say, oops, we don't care about validation anymore.

00:30:37.920 --> 00:30:45.439
So some of the challenges has come, but also very cool opportunities for colleagues to explore and innovate in those spaces, right?

00:30:45.439 --> 00:30:47.280
Because it's pretty open at the moment.

00:30:48.160 --> 00:30:49.119
I like that.

00:30:49.119 --> 00:30:51.920
I like the focus on that this is an opportunity to innovate.

00:30:51.920 --> 00:30:54.560
It's not just a top down mandate that you have to like deal with.

00:30:55.280 --> 00:30:57.040
Fantastic.

00:30:57.040 --> 00:30:59.439
Thank you, Renato, for hopping in with your experience.

00:30:59.439 --> 00:30:59.920
I loved it.

00:31:00.479 --> 00:31:05.520
I wanted to ask a couple of questions that can be pretty quick to answer.

00:31:05.520 --> 00:31:08.239
One is, what's your costume for Halloween?

00:31:09.199 --> 00:31:10.319
Are you a Halloween person?

00:31:10.319 --> 00:31:10.959
Somebody asked that.

00:31:10.959 --> 00:31:11.760
I thought it was really fun.

00:31:13.760 --> 00:31:21.599
I don't, I'm afraid I don't think I really celebrate Halloween routinely, but I have been known to like don on fancy crazy hats.

00:31:22.160 --> 00:31:24.160
And walk around in a wizard's robe.

00:31:24.160 --> 00:31:26.880
But that was years back in college.

00:31:28.160 --> 00:31:28.880
I love it.

00:31:28.880 --> 00:31:34.560
Mine's usually I have one witch hat and it doesn't fit my head, but I clip it on anyway.

00:31:34.560 --> 00:31:35.599
That's my costume.

00:31:37.199 --> 00:31:40.560
I was not prepared to answer what's my Halloween costume.

00:31:40.560 --> 00:31:43.599
I always love, there's always a question that ends up in Flutter that's funny.

00:31:44.400 --> 00:31:47.920
And I wanted to ask one more that I think will be quick, but it's on topic.

00:31:48.959 --> 00:31:51.359
And it's just a context building question for us.

00:31:52.160 --> 00:31:52.719
I lost it.

00:31:54.000 --> 00:31:54.719
I lost it.

00:31:54.719 --> 00:31:55.359
There we go.

00:31:55.359 --> 00:31:58.560
It was, what is your workflow and what software do you use?

00:31:58.560 --> 00:32:03.680
And I think that that is a nice thing to do at the little halfway mark or more than halfway mark here.

00:32:05.439 --> 00:32:09.199
Maybe the technology stack that your team works with to get their job done.

00:32:10.160 --> 00:32:12.160
I think it's primarily Jira, right?

00:32:12.160 --> 00:32:15.839
If you talk about technical product development, that would be the answer.

00:32:15.839 --> 00:32:20.880
But in terms of creating workflows, because a lot of the work from our,

00:32:21.760 --> 00:32:25.680
my leadership team's perspective with me is the strategic piece, right?

00:32:25.680 --> 00:32:28.959
So it's like, there's no given defined workflow already.

00:32:28.959 --> 00:32:30.880
You literally have to innovate as you go.

00:32:31.839 --> 00:32:35.839
There we use Agile tools like business mapping and Kanban,

00:32:37.439 --> 00:32:42.079
kind of like Klaxons to like really like draw it out piece by piece.

00:32:42.079 --> 00:32:47.280
We have a tool called Draw.io where we use that to kind of figure out process maps,

00:32:47.280 --> 00:32:52.160
but it's basically really dependent on what you're doing and what tool fits.

00:32:52.800 --> 00:32:53.199
Okay.

00:32:53.199 --> 00:32:56.959
So that kind of answers the workflow part for sure.

00:32:56.959 --> 00:32:58.800
And we use Jira too.

00:32:58.800 --> 00:33:00.079
Everybody, let me know what you use.

00:33:00.079 --> 00:33:05.599
Do you use Jira or do you use Asana or Monday or something else?

00:33:05.599 --> 00:33:06.239
I'm curious.

00:33:06.880 --> 00:33:07.680
Erin says Jira.

00:33:08.319 --> 00:33:11.119
And then what about tools that are data science tools

00:33:11.119 --> 00:33:12.880
or development tools that your team uses?

00:33:13.599 --> 00:33:15.839
So I see what you're asking.

00:33:15.839 --> 00:33:17.920
So basically it has layers.

00:33:17.920 --> 00:33:23.280
What we have from Posit is our infrastructure platform,

00:33:23.280 --> 00:33:25.199
which is called Copernicus internally.

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:32.319
What it is, is Posit Workbench, Posit Connect and Posit Package Manager combined into three.

00:33:32.959 --> 00:33:36.239
And as a wrapper on top of that, we have our own

00:33:36.239 --> 00:33:40.079
in-house developed statistical computing environment, which we call RISE.

00:33:40.719 --> 00:33:47.119
And this environment has been developed with a specific mind to connect to the Posit piece,

00:33:47.119 --> 00:33:51.520
but also at the same time, be open to whatever other ideas to come later on.

00:33:52.479 --> 00:33:55.439
At the moment, it accommodates SAS and R

00:33:55.439 --> 00:34:00.800
with the intention that the SAS part will be off in the next couple of years to come.

00:34:00.800 --> 00:34:02.640
So that's what it looks like.

00:34:03.599 --> 00:34:05.680
I think that that's probably part of what the question was.

00:34:05.680 --> 00:34:09.520
It was like, we're talking about this transition from closed source to open source,

00:34:09.520 --> 00:34:14.080
but then we never actually said it's from SAS to R or from SAS to Python or whatever.

00:34:15.120 --> 00:34:17.439
So thank you, anonymous asker, for asking that.

00:34:17.439 --> 00:34:22.320
And in the pharma industry, still SAS is a major player, right?

00:34:23.520 --> 00:34:27.679
Many companies still depend on SAS for their solutioning.

00:34:27.679 --> 00:34:32.719
I think where we started seeing advantages and pushing it,

00:34:33.280 --> 00:34:37.199
also in my previous role in the stats methods lead,

00:34:38.080 --> 00:34:42.879
what we observed is more and more the regulatory demands talk about simulating.

00:34:43.840 --> 00:34:46.959
And if you are running large scale simulation,

00:34:46.959 --> 00:34:49.600
I think nobody really in their sane mind uses SAS.

00:34:50.639 --> 00:34:51.600
Sorry, SAS.

00:34:51.600 --> 00:34:54.879
And then you are using evidently R,

00:34:55.600 --> 00:35:01.360
but then it wasn't really like as sophisticated solution as was it offers.

00:35:02.560 --> 00:35:04.719
So it was not cloud-based.

00:35:04.719 --> 00:35:08.399
It was an internal HPC servers that we used to use.

00:35:08.959 --> 00:35:12.000
And that was really lengthy and time consuming.

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:17.120
So when you are facing regulatory questions or somehow time limit on,

00:35:17.120 --> 00:35:20.239
you need to do your simulations, but also you don't have all year to do it.

00:35:20.879 --> 00:35:24.639
It became very clear that colleagues were struggling internally to somehow

00:35:24.639 --> 00:35:28.239
like manage the scope of simulation without compromising the science part,

00:35:28.239 --> 00:35:31.280
but also deliver in time so that you can answer the questions

00:35:31.280 --> 00:35:32.800
that we're initially hunting for.

00:35:33.919 --> 00:35:37.760
And I can tell you one of the first instances of implementing Copernicus,

00:35:38.719 --> 00:35:43.840
one team reported that their simulation has now become 500 times faster.

00:35:44.879 --> 00:35:48.159
And those are numbers and metrics that no one can deny.

00:35:48.159 --> 00:35:50.159
And it speaks to everybody,

00:35:50.159 --> 00:35:54.000
to the colleagues who are hands-on running this because they feel the pain,

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:59.679
but also to the leadership who is now being able to go to their leadership beyond

00:36:00.320 --> 00:36:03.360
and talk about my team just delivered this like much,

00:36:03.360 --> 00:36:05.840
much faster than what they would be able to do before.

00:36:05.840 --> 00:36:06.959
And these things matter.

00:36:07.760 --> 00:36:10.479
So creating these kinds of stories,

00:36:10.479 --> 00:36:14.879
emphasizing those in the community kind of builds that credibility over time

00:36:15.600 --> 00:36:17.120
to say over and over again,

00:36:17.120 --> 00:36:20.080
you move, it's not just a language shift.

00:36:21.199 --> 00:36:23.040
It actually creates value,

00:36:23.040 --> 00:36:25.280
which you never would be able to tap into

00:36:25.919 --> 00:36:28.959
using the previous infrastructure and tools.

00:36:28.959 --> 00:36:29.679
And now you can.

00:36:30.959 --> 00:36:32.239
That's amazing.

00:36:33.040 --> 00:36:35.360
It's so funny that you say that because some of the other people

00:36:35.360 --> 00:36:38.000
that we've talked to at other pharma companies,

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:40.560
actually, and I'm thinking about like Takeda and others

00:36:43.439 --> 00:36:45.439
had that similar discussion.

00:36:45.439 --> 00:36:48.320
Harvey Lieberman also mentioned this about speed.

00:36:48.320 --> 00:36:50.879
It's like there was something that took a really long time

00:36:50.879 --> 00:36:52.879
and people were either doing it manually

00:36:52.879 --> 00:36:55.760
or doing it sort of half manually.

00:36:55.760 --> 00:36:58.239
And it was taking weeks or months to do it.

00:36:58.239 --> 00:37:00.560
And then, you know, we take the time,

00:37:00.560 --> 00:37:04.080
we invest the time to get it switched over to an open source solution like our,

00:37:04.080 --> 00:37:06.959
and then it takes a day or it takes half an hour

00:37:06.959 --> 00:37:08.560
or it takes somebody, you know,

00:37:09.280 --> 00:37:12.000
part of their work week instead of several work weeks.

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:12.800
That's amazing.

00:37:12.800 --> 00:37:16.719
I wanted to also shout out a anonymous question

00:37:16.719 --> 00:37:18.320
that was asked in the Slido

00:37:18.320 --> 00:37:22.239
that I also turned into a open text question in Slido

00:37:22.239 --> 00:37:23.840
for everybody to answer.

00:37:23.840 --> 00:37:26.399
There are so many great responses there.

00:37:26.399 --> 00:37:27.600
So definitely go add yours.

00:37:27.600 --> 00:37:31.600
And it was, how can someone start getting into open source,

00:37:31.600 --> 00:37:35.760
especially if they have been working on proprietary software all their life?

00:37:36.639 --> 00:37:38.719
There are several examples there.

00:37:38.719 --> 00:37:40.719
Judy, did you want to add anything really quickly?

00:37:41.280 --> 00:37:42.959
Absolutely.

00:37:42.959 --> 00:37:45.520
And I think that's a really good question

00:37:45.520 --> 00:37:47.199
and it's a real question, right?

00:37:47.199 --> 00:37:48.959
It's not just like I want to,

00:37:48.959 --> 00:37:50.159
but how do I do that?

00:37:51.600 --> 00:37:53.280
I think long story short,

00:37:53.280 --> 00:37:55.439
my way and maybe here,

00:37:55.439 --> 00:37:58.320
I think Marlene was asking about some of the failures

00:37:58.320 --> 00:38:00.560
or struggles that have happened.

00:38:00.560 --> 00:38:01.919
I can kind of relate to that.

00:38:01.919 --> 00:38:06.800
This is one of my previous initiatives and how it went.

00:38:06.800 --> 00:38:09.280
So by definition, by design,

00:38:09.280 --> 00:38:12.800
I was in my career developing new approaches

00:38:12.800 --> 00:38:13.919
and trying to convince people

00:38:13.919 --> 00:38:14.959
that this is the way to go

00:38:14.959 --> 00:38:16.399
and move away from the old stuff,

00:38:16.399 --> 00:38:18.080
like forget about open source in general,

00:38:18.080 --> 00:38:18.959
in stats methods.

00:38:19.919 --> 00:38:24.719
And oftentimes I have struggled with that, right?

00:38:24.719 --> 00:38:26.719
And one of the biggest pain points

00:38:26.719 --> 00:38:28.719
that I heard over and over again

00:38:28.719 --> 00:38:29.919
was I don't have time.

00:38:31.280 --> 00:38:34.800
I'm already so full with my plate

00:38:34.800 --> 00:38:37.840
that if you think that I can carve out 20% of my time

00:38:37.840 --> 00:38:39.199
and learn something, forget it.

00:38:39.199 --> 00:38:40.080
It's not going to happen.

00:38:40.719 --> 00:38:44.239
And one of the, I mean, it's just so true, right?

00:38:45.120 --> 00:38:46.479
We struggle with it.

00:38:46.479 --> 00:38:48.320
It's easy for leaders to say,

00:38:48.320 --> 00:38:49.360
oh, we'll just learn it.

00:38:50.399 --> 00:38:50.959
How?

00:38:50.959 --> 00:38:53.760
Where is that extra amount of time going to come from?

00:38:54.800 --> 00:38:56.879
And that's a struggle.

00:38:56.879 --> 00:38:59.120
What I decided to do differently

00:38:59.120 --> 00:39:02.639
in this particular topic of learning

00:39:02.639 --> 00:39:04.719
R or other tools beyond SAS

00:39:05.280 --> 00:39:09.760
was try to overlap that with their day-to-day,

00:39:10.399 --> 00:39:13.600
which basically means you are anyway tasked

00:39:13.600 --> 00:39:16.639
in executing a particular activity

00:39:17.280 --> 00:39:18.959
and you used to do it in SAS.

00:39:19.600 --> 00:39:22.000
Let me find you a buddy or a mentor

00:39:22.000 --> 00:39:26.000
or this community organizers who are our coaches.

00:39:27.040 --> 00:39:29.760
If we can see you can implement the same template

00:39:29.760 --> 00:39:31.760
using a different language,

00:39:32.560 --> 00:39:36.080
but now you are serving your own work

00:39:36.080 --> 00:39:38.000
at the same time serving the community.

00:39:39.199 --> 00:39:43.199
And this type of overlapping model worked very nicely,

00:39:43.199 --> 00:39:45.360
is working very nicely for Boringa.

00:39:45.360 --> 00:39:47.520
And I'm talking from a global company perspective.

00:39:47.520 --> 00:39:49.120
There's so many hundreds of people.

00:39:50.159 --> 00:39:52.080
It's not always easy to find this,

00:39:52.080 --> 00:39:55.679
but I can tell you that I've been able to find this

00:39:55.679 --> 00:39:56.560
in many cases.

00:39:56.560 --> 00:40:01.679
It's like pushing back on ideas

00:40:01.679 --> 00:40:02.959
where you hear from people,

00:40:02.959 --> 00:40:05.679
oh, I can just retrospectively implement something

00:40:06.639 --> 00:40:08.159
and immediately realize

00:40:08.159 --> 00:40:10.560
that retrospective implementation

00:40:10.560 --> 00:40:12.320
is basically just add onto your plate

00:40:12.320 --> 00:40:14.560
without you being able to tell the company

00:40:14.560 --> 00:40:16.479
and here is how I served business too.

00:40:17.760 --> 00:40:20.639
So it takes a little bit of courage and boldness to say,

00:40:20.639 --> 00:40:24.560
I'm confident I can start on this as a real deliverable.

00:40:24.560 --> 00:40:25.679
And if I face problems,

00:40:25.679 --> 00:40:27.840
my community is there to back me up

00:40:27.840 --> 00:40:29.040
and solve those problems.

00:40:29.679 --> 00:40:32.159
So it's not like you don't feel alone.

00:40:32.719 --> 00:40:33.760
We are with you,

00:40:33.760 --> 00:40:36.080
but at the same time have a little bit of courage

00:40:36.080 --> 00:40:37.679
to come into something,

00:40:38.879 --> 00:40:43.120
which then is a very nice topic for the leadership to say,

00:40:43.120 --> 00:40:45.199
and here is how I also did my work.

00:40:46.080 --> 00:40:48.639
This model has been working nicely.

00:40:48.639 --> 00:40:52.719
I can tell you an example of one of the things

00:40:52.719 --> 00:40:54.879
that any clinical trialist have to do

00:40:54.879 --> 00:40:56.560
is monitor data as they come in

00:40:56.560 --> 00:40:57.760
all throughout the conduct.

00:40:58.800 --> 00:41:00.959
And we do this in a quality review meeting,

00:41:00.959 --> 00:41:02.320
which happens every few months.

00:41:03.360 --> 00:41:05.600
And in the middle of this year,

00:41:05.600 --> 00:41:08.560
we wrote an email to the entire company and said,

00:41:08.560 --> 00:41:09.760
and we are going to do this

00:41:09.760 --> 00:41:11.840
in an interactive, shiny fashion, period.

00:41:12.719 --> 00:41:16.159
Let's move away from this thousands pages of PDF outputs,

00:41:16.159 --> 00:41:18.080
which makes everybody's life difficult.

00:41:19.120 --> 00:41:22.399
And there was this pushback to say,

00:41:22.959 --> 00:41:25.520
how are we going to implement these things

00:41:25.520 --> 00:41:27.679
on top of the daily work?

00:41:28.399 --> 00:41:32.000
What we were able to do is take people

00:41:32.000 --> 00:41:34.879
who were already in charge of implementing these reviews,

00:41:35.520 --> 00:41:37.840
instead of creating SAS based PDFs,

00:41:38.479 --> 00:41:39.840
they were implementing Shiny

00:41:39.840 --> 00:41:41.600
with the help of the community support.

00:41:42.560 --> 00:41:45.280
And it simultaneously helped build up templates

00:41:45.280 --> 00:41:47.280
for other later trials to use.

00:41:48.080 --> 00:41:50.639
So it was basically like you learn suddenly

00:41:50.639 --> 00:41:52.399
your work can create value,

00:41:52.399 --> 00:41:53.360
not just for now,

00:41:53.919 --> 00:41:55.360
but also become scalable

00:41:55.360 --> 00:41:58.639
so that it can be used for the future work

00:41:58.639 --> 00:42:00.639
that you may have or your colleagues may have.

00:42:01.919 --> 00:42:03.280
And I made this reference

00:42:03.280 --> 00:42:04.959
to the software development team,

00:42:06.479 --> 00:42:09.439
which is I really need to plug them a little bit here.

00:42:10.479 --> 00:42:12.479
One of the struggles we have had,

00:42:12.479 --> 00:42:15.040
and many of you have experienced

00:42:15.040 --> 00:42:17.360
when it comes to developing tools and templates,

00:42:17.360 --> 00:42:21.120
many of us think of this as a one-time activity.

00:42:21.120 --> 00:42:22.320
Like you just do something,

00:42:22.320 --> 00:42:23.840
it works for the moment,

00:42:23.840 --> 00:42:26.639
but we forget that there is a part around maintenance.

00:42:28.080 --> 00:42:30.159
So creating a template is easy,

00:42:30.159 --> 00:42:33.199
maintaining it and making it still working

00:42:33.199 --> 00:42:36.080
after two years is the hard part, right?

00:42:36.080 --> 00:42:38.479
And one of the pieces that we also realize,

00:42:38.479 --> 00:42:42.000
and I think many of you will acknowledge it,

00:42:42.000 --> 00:42:46.320
it is so hard to work with someone else's code, right?

00:42:46.320 --> 00:42:48.159
This is not an easy activity to say,

00:42:48.159 --> 00:42:50.639
oh, give me some code and I will make it.

00:42:50.639 --> 00:42:52.080
Fantastic, it's not easy.

00:42:53.120 --> 00:42:55.360
So one of the things we decided to do

00:42:55.360 --> 00:42:58.879
was help the community by building modules

00:42:58.879 --> 00:43:01.520
or smaller code chunks.

00:43:02.560 --> 00:43:06.159
And then the community's job is to take those modules

00:43:06.159 --> 00:43:08.080
and then they can mix and match

00:43:08.080 --> 00:43:09.679
in whichever way they sound fit

00:43:09.679 --> 00:43:12.000
and build a bigger app out of it.

00:43:12.560 --> 00:43:15.360
And the quality of modules is controlled

00:43:15.360 --> 00:43:17.360
because it's built by the same team

00:43:18.320 --> 00:43:21.360
who are at the top of their game in software development

00:43:21.360 --> 00:43:22.719
and writing a good piece of software,

00:43:22.719 --> 00:43:23.600
they know how to do that.

00:43:24.479 --> 00:43:27.919
So that was one way of a solution to scale this piece,

00:43:27.919 --> 00:43:30.320
simultaneously controlling for the quality

00:43:30.320 --> 00:43:31.360
and maintenance with.

00:43:32.239 --> 00:43:32.719
I love it.

00:43:35.280 --> 00:43:37.360
They're giving their colleagues Legos

00:43:37.360 --> 00:43:40.000
to build and put together things that work

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:41.360
and they're high quality Legos.

00:43:41.360 --> 00:43:43.040
So everyone might put them together differently,

00:43:43.040 --> 00:43:44.479
but at least the Legos work.

00:43:44.479 --> 00:43:45.360
I like that.

00:43:45.360 --> 00:43:48.399
And I saw lots of heads nodding when you said,

00:43:48.399 --> 00:43:50.639
it's so hard to use other people's code.

00:43:52.159 --> 00:43:55.280
And Tim said, it's hard for me to work with my code

00:43:55.280 --> 00:43:58.479
since me in the past was not kind to present day me

00:43:58.479 --> 00:43:59.919
and commenting my code.

00:43:59.919 --> 00:44:02.959
Tim, yes, absolutely.

00:44:02.959 --> 00:44:04.560
I will come back next day and go,

00:44:04.560 --> 00:44:05.840
what was I thinking?

00:44:05.840 --> 00:44:06.560
What was I doing?

00:44:06.560 --> 00:44:09.120
And now in today's day and age,

00:44:10.959 --> 00:44:12.320
what was chat GPT thinking?

00:44:12.320 --> 00:44:13.760
What was Claude thinking?

00:44:13.760 --> 00:44:16.000
Why didn't I write down or discern better

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:16.719
what they were doing?

00:44:17.439 --> 00:44:19.520
Arsenis, I saw that you had a question in Slido.

00:44:19.520 --> 00:44:22.320
Would you like to unmute and ask that live?

00:44:22.320 --> 00:44:24.239
We've got about 10 minutes left with Judy.

00:44:24.959 --> 00:44:25.520
Sure.

00:44:25.520 --> 00:44:26.239
Thanks Libby.

00:44:26.239 --> 00:44:29.679
And thank you very much Judy for meeting,

00:44:29.679 --> 00:44:31.199
for talking with us today.

00:44:32.320 --> 00:44:34.239
So my question is about this thing

00:44:34.239 --> 00:44:36.800
that Libby just mentioned, which is documentation.

00:44:36.800 --> 00:44:41.360
So you actually mentioned when you were introducing

00:44:41.360 --> 00:44:43.520
kind of what you do and the change

00:44:44.000 --> 00:44:46.000
that you all are making at Bargainer,

00:44:46.000 --> 00:44:49.280
that documentation is one of the things

00:44:49.280 --> 00:44:50.719
that you kind of work on.

00:44:50.719 --> 00:44:53.199
And what I'd like to know is how it is

00:44:53.199 --> 00:44:56.399
that you all motivate data professionals,

00:44:56.399 --> 00:44:58.639
especially folks that are beginners in open source

00:44:58.639 --> 00:45:02.080
and all that who typically might not care

00:45:02.080 --> 00:45:03.600
that much about documentation

00:45:03.600 --> 00:45:06.560
when you get into a project to document.

00:45:06.560 --> 00:45:08.320
What are some of the things that you do for that?

00:45:09.840 --> 00:45:10.879
That's a great question.

00:45:10.879 --> 00:45:14.719
And I can tell you, it's not just the initial people

00:45:14.719 --> 00:45:17.120
getting in, nobody likes documentation.

00:45:17.120 --> 00:45:18.399
Let's just like admit it.

00:45:19.600 --> 00:45:22.800
It's also good to admit that we are

00:45:22.800 --> 00:45:25.439
in this highly regulated industry workspace.

00:45:26.000 --> 00:45:28.000
Documentation is something you do

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:29.679
as part of your job requirement.

00:45:29.679 --> 00:45:31.840
This is not an optional story that you say,

00:45:31.840 --> 00:45:34.080
oh yeah, I did something I forgot.

00:45:34.080 --> 00:45:36.479
And now there is no traceability or reproducibility

00:45:36.479 --> 00:45:37.360
of what you have done.

00:45:37.360 --> 00:45:39.120
And therefore what decisions you have made,

00:45:39.120 --> 00:45:40.639
this comes up in audits.

00:45:41.520 --> 00:45:44.239
And then you get like a smack down from your leadership,

00:45:44.239 --> 00:45:46.800
say how bad this is not good.

00:45:47.520 --> 00:45:48.959
This has happened historically.

00:45:48.959 --> 00:45:53.520
I mean, my company is also more than 150 years old.

00:45:54.639 --> 00:45:56.000
They have learned their lessons.

00:45:56.000 --> 00:45:59.360
Therefore there's emphasis on maintaining documentation.

00:45:59.919 --> 00:46:02.959
What was critical for us to realize

00:46:02.959 --> 00:46:05.600
that because we are defining a whole new world,

00:46:06.560 --> 00:46:09.199
there was no templates on documents

00:46:09.199 --> 00:46:10.639
that we could rely on, right?

00:46:10.639 --> 00:46:13.600
Some of this documentation had to be created as we go.

00:46:14.639 --> 00:46:17.439
I touched upon this topic around validation.

00:46:17.439 --> 00:46:18.879
That was one example, right?

00:46:18.879 --> 00:46:22.080
You're writing these documents to define the process

00:46:22.080 --> 00:46:24.080
and who does what and who is checking.

00:46:24.719 --> 00:46:27.600
You also have to talk about where is this saved.

00:46:27.600 --> 00:46:29.919
And there's this layers to the story.

00:46:31.600 --> 00:46:33.840
What I think internally, I can share

00:46:33.840 --> 00:46:36.719
that it has been not so strugglesome

00:46:36.719 --> 00:46:40.639
because people already had the habit of documenting things.

00:46:41.439 --> 00:46:42.959
It's just about saying,

00:46:42.959 --> 00:46:44.239
and this process comes

00:46:44.239 --> 00:46:46.239
with this documentation responsibility.

00:46:46.239 --> 00:46:47.360
So it wasn't like,

00:46:47.360 --> 00:46:51.600
this part was not movers and shakers for colleagues

00:46:51.600 --> 00:46:55.360
because they're already used to that conception of like,

00:46:55.360 --> 00:46:57.439
yeah, if I do something, I need to document.

00:46:58.959 --> 00:46:59.760
I hope that helped.

00:47:00.479 --> 00:47:02.320
Yeah, documentation's always rough.

00:47:03.040 --> 00:47:04.000
I know, right?

00:47:04.000 --> 00:47:07.679
But here, LLMs have given us an advantage for sure.

00:47:07.679 --> 00:47:11.679
I think one of the first things people started talking about

00:47:12.719 --> 00:47:17.199
LLMs where can we essentially take away some of these tasks

00:47:17.760 --> 00:47:19.600
and do it in a more efficient way.

00:47:19.600 --> 00:47:21.439
And I think that's definitely,

00:47:21.439 --> 00:47:24.159
I mean, you have probably seen examples in the industry

00:47:24.159 --> 00:47:25.600
that this is already happening.

00:47:25.600 --> 00:47:27.040
Some of this typical documentation

00:47:27.040 --> 00:47:28.479
that I created over and over again,

00:47:29.120 --> 00:47:32.000
enough templates to feed it to the LLM

00:47:32.239 --> 00:47:33.760
and say, okay, I need this and that.

00:47:33.760 --> 00:47:34.800
Can you create a draft?

00:47:35.439 --> 00:47:35.840
Great.

00:47:35.840 --> 00:47:38.239
And then you get the tedious task of editing it

00:47:38.239 --> 00:47:39.040
and make sure it's right.

00:47:39.600 --> 00:47:41.040
Arsanis, thank you for that question.

00:47:42.159 --> 00:47:46.399
Let's hop over to a question that I saw Eric asked.

00:47:46.399 --> 00:47:47.679
I hope Eric is still here.

00:47:47.679 --> 00:47:48.560
Yes, he's still here.

00:47:49.439 --> 00:47:50.800
I like this question, Eric,

00:47:50.800 --> 00:47:53.679
because I think that Doody has something to say

00:47:53.679 --> 00:47:54.239
about this one.

00:47:56.080 --> 00:47:58.959
Yeah, I'm really enjoying this content so far.

00:47:58.959 --> 00:48:00.560
Sorry, I was fashionably late.

00:48:00.560 --> 00:48:02.719
When you get in the shining of the bug and things happen,

00:48:02.719 --> 00:48:04.080
time flies, but nonetheless,

00:48:05.360 --> 00:48:07.679
we've all, like I said, in life sciences,

00:48:07.679 --> 00:48:09.040
I'm part of life sciences too.

00:48:09.040 --> 00:48:11.600
And we know that open source is growing immensely

00:48:11.600 --> 00:48:14.719
into how we're developing these innovative capabilities.

00:48:15.439 --> 00:48:17.040
It's one thing to consume,

00:48:17.040 --> 00:48:19.360
like the open source content out there,

00:48:19.360 --> 00:48:22.000
such as using farmer's packages and whatnot.

00:48:22.000 --> 00:48:25.199
But it's another to help motivate people

00:48:25.199 --> 00:48:28.560
in your organization to want to keep up

00:48:28.560 --> 00:48:30.239
with the pulse of what's happening,

00:48:30.239 --> 00:48:32.639
even if they're not necessarily contributing back to it,

00:48:32.639 --> 00:48:34.639
at least being aware of what's happening.

00:48:35.199 --> 00:48:36.479
So I have some thoughts,

00:48:36.479 --> 00:48:38.560
but I'd like to hear what you have to say

00:48:38.560 --> 00:48:41.520
about how do you motivate people on your team

00:48:41.520 --> 00:48:44.639
or your colleagues to not just consume these tools,

00:48:44.639 --> 00:48:46.800
really see what's happening out there

00:48:46.800 --> 00:48:48.800
and really being abreast of what's happening

00:48:48.800 --> 00:48:50.320
in the latest and greatest

00:48:50.320 --> 00:48:51.840
in some of these developments out there.

00:48:51.840 --> 00:48:52.879
And thanks.

00:48:52.879 --> 00:48:55.360
I think that question really resonates with me.

00:48:55.360 --> 00:48:56.159
Libby was right.

00:48:56.639 --> 00:49:00.239
It's basically this challenge also,

00:49:00.239 --> 00:49:02.479
which comes with having worked

00:49:02.479 --> 00:49:04.399
in a closed source environment

00:49:04.399 --> 00:49:08.000
where we would just be concerned with our templates,

00:49:08.000 --> 00:49:10.560
our way of doing it, our way of reporting it,

00:49:10.560 --> 00:49:14.719
and then forget about what are other people doing.

00:49:15.360 --> 00:49:18.879
And I think it has started to permeate.

00:49:18.879 --> 00:49:20.719
I would not say we are already there

00:49:20.719 --> 00:49:23.040
doing 100% of external awareness,

00:49:23.040 --> 00:49:26.479
but what has helped is my team

00:49:26.479 --> 00:49:29.360
is essentially a group of connected individuals

00:49:29.360 --> 00:49:32.320
who are no longer just working in one silo

00:49:32.320 --> 00:49:33.679
that they are responsible for.

00:49:34.239 --> 00:49:36.959
I see this like mashing effect to say,

00:49:36.959 --> 00:49:39.280
like coming together to help each other

00:49:39.280 --> 00:49:40.879
and they all see the bigger picture.

00:49:41.520 --> 00:49:44.000
Part of that is then sending these individuals

00:49:44.000 --> 00:49:46.479
or encouraging them to attend conferences

00:49:46.479 --> 00:49:48.320
like Fawzit conference, for example,

00:49:48.320 --> 00:49:49.840
or a fuse or a DIA.

00:49:50.800 --> 00:49:54.479
In the US, I was hosting a couple of sessions

00:49:54.479 --> 00:49:56.239
in the regulatory industry stats workshop,

00:49:56.239 --> 00:49:59.280
like going to places, engaging with colleagues,

00:50:00.239 --> 00:50:02.080
and then also bringing that back

00:50:02.080 --> 00:50:04.000
to simulate that excitement to say

00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:05.520
a lot of things are happening

00:50:06.080 --> 00:50:08.000
and there is a lot to learn and a lot to give

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:09.760
and a lot to like exchange on.

00:50:10.639 --> 00:50:13.040
But I think that this is going to take some time

00:50:13.040 --> 00:50:14.479
to really like permeate

00:50:14.479 --> 00:50:16.239
at every level of the organization.

00:50:16.239 --> 00:50:19.040
I would still say this is particularly noticeable

00:50:19.040 --> 00:50:21.600
in people who are directly involved

00:50:21.600 --> 00:50:24.000
in implementing pieces in open source

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:26.320
and internally in the working group,

00:50:26.320 --> 00:50:29.919
but I would not say that this happens over and across.

00:50:29.919 --> 00:50:31.760
This is something, a work in progress

00:50:31.760 --> 00:50:34.159
and also an important piece.

00:50:35.360 --> 00:50:39.439
I've been telling people this part around giving back.

00:50:40.000 --> 00:50:43.040
I think some of you may know

00:50:43.040 --> 00:50:46.080
that we had made this entire modular framework,

00:50:46.159 --> 00:50:49.120
which we call the Vinci open source.

00:50:49.120 --> 00:50:49.919
It's available.

00:50:49.919 --> 00:50:50.879
You can check it out,

00:50:51.679 --> 00:50:54.719
but it's also thinking about all these resources

00:50:54.719 --> 00:50:56.080
that we are creating internally.

00:50:56.080 --> 00:50:57.600
Somebody talked about learning.

00:50:58.639 --> 00:51:00.560
How do we start internally?

00:51:00.560 --> 00:51:03.679
We have created some really cool resources,

00:51:03.679 --> 00:51:06.239
like people are handwriting resources sometimes

00:51:06.239 --> 00:51:09.600
or coming together from different sources.

00:51:10.399 --> 00:51:12.719
My first thought was, can we make that open source?

00:51:13.360 --> 00:51:15.040
So hopefully next year,

00:51:15.040 --> 00:51:17.840
we will also push some of these internal developed tools

00:51:17.840 --> 00:51:21.040
and templates and products in the open source space.

00:51:21.040 --> 00:51:23.840
Each of this should help the community

00:51:23.840 --> 00:51:27.199
in small and large way to get there together.

00:51:30.560 --> 00:51:32.080
I'm curious, like your own thoughts.

00:51:32.080 --> 00:51:33.520
You said you had some thoughts of your own.

00:51:33.520 --> 00:51:34.719
I'm very curious to also.

00:51:35.679 --> 00:51:38.560
Well, yeah, you capture a lot of my thoughts too.

00:51:39.360 --> 00:51:42.080
There was a situation that really motivated it.

00:51:42.080 --> 00:51:44.399
I had a really talented colleague come to me

00:51:45.120 --> 00:51:46.879
with a prototype Shiny app

00:51:46.879 --> 00:51:50.000
that was doing like high level exploratory data analysis.

00:51:50.719 --> 00:51:54.879
And I said, this looks good, but have you heard of Teal?

00:51:55.760 --> 00:51:58.080
And I showed him this and literally he's like,

00:51:58.080 --> 00:52:01.120
if I had known this, I would never have built this.

00:52:01.120 --> 00:52:02.479
Teal does everything I need.

00:52:02.479 --> 00:52:04.639
So it's just like trying to figure out

00:52:04.639 --> 00:52:07.040
how to put these little breadcrumbs in

00:52:07.040 --> 00:52:08.800
and obviously user group,

00:52:08.800 --> 00:52:10.800
internal user groups are one way of doing that.

00:52:10.800 --> 00:52:13.840
So that people come at one kind of cadence,

00:52:13.840 --> 00:52:16.239
regular cadence to inform them.

00:52:16.239 --> 00:52:19.199
But yeah, like you said, a well-connected team

00:52:19.199 --> 00:52:21.520
and just trying to spread that knowledge out,

00:52:21.520 --> 00:52:25.120
but in a way that the other people want to join

00:52:25.120 --> 00:52:26.399
on that learning journey

00:52:26.399 --> 00:52:28.560
and not just feel like they're forced to.

00:52:28.560 --> 00:52:30.399
I would agree with you, it's a work in progress.

00:52:31.040 --> 00:52:32.479
It's about awareness, right?

00:52:33.600 --> 00:52:34.479
If people aren't aware,

00:52:34.479 --> 00:52:36.479
they can't be excited about something.

00:52:36.479 --> 00:52:42.399
And Judy had said, with the health of the community

00:52:42.399 --> 00:52:44.000
getting better inside of Boehringer,

00:52:44.560 --> 00:52:46.399
that you've even had people

00:52:46.399 --> 00:52:48.239
who are talking to you about jobs

00:52:48.239 --> 00:52:49.199
and those people are like,

00:52:50.000 --> 00:52:51.679
I don't really care what the payer of the job is.

00:52:51.679 --> 00:52:53.280
Do I get to use the new tools?

00:52:53.280 --> 00:52:55.199
Do I get to do the fun, cool stuff?

00:52:55.840 --> 00:52:57.919
So you're obviously doing something right

00:52:57.919 --> 00:53:00.159
with creating a sense of anticipation

00:53:00.159 --> 00:53:01.280
around this cool new stuff.

00:53:03.439 --> 00:53:04.159
Yeah, I love it.

00:53:04.159 --> 00:53:07.120
I was so glad to hear that

00:53:07.120 --> 00:53:09.520
and what Libby just shared as an anecdote,

00:53:09.520 --> 00:53:11.040
it actually happened internally.

00:53:11.040 --> 00:53:14.239
So I was talking to a colleague about a certain role

00:53:14.239 --> 00:53:17.760
and usually would expect people talk about titles,

00:53:17.760 --> 00:53:20.879
compensation, benefits, even team.

00:53:20.879 --> 00:53:22.800
They ask who is this time?

00:53:22.800 --> 00:53:25.040
I just want to use all the latest technology.

00:53:25.040 --> 00:53:26.719
Don't make me work the old way.

00:53:27.439 --> 00:53:30.560
Yeah, I was like, whoa, that's inspiring.

00:53:30.560 --> 00:53:32.879
I had never heard somebody talk about it.

00:53:32.879 --> 00:53:37.439
So there are these really positive signs, I must say.

00:53:38.159 --> 00:53:41.600
So we are all feeling community-wise very hopeful

00:53:41.600 --> 00:53:45.439
that this is going to be a good way to get into

00:53:45.439 --> 00:53:46.320
and be successful.

00:53:46.320 --> 00:53:48.320
And I wish all of you guys the same.

00:53:48.320 --> 00:53:52.000
I think we are at one hour mark, Libby.

00:53:52.560 --> 00:53:53.760
We are, I know.

00:53:53.760 --> 00:53:55.600
We've gone straight to the line.

00:53:55.600 --> 00:53:58.000
Well, Judy, I really, really appreciate you

00:53:58.000 --> 00:53:58.719
hanging out with us.

00:53:58.719 --> 00:54:00.080
I'm sure you've got some place to be.

00:54:00.959 --> 00:54:03.120
I want to thank you for all of the wisdom.

00:54:03.120 --> 00:54:05.520
Thank you to the community for hanging out with us.

00:54:05.520 --> 00:54:07.439
You can save the chat if it has been helpful.

00:54:07.439 --> 00:54:08.800
Top right corner, there's three dots.

00:54:09.679 --> 00:54:13.600
And we are really excited to see you next week.

00:54:13.600 --> 00:54:16.560
We have Arielle Dror, Director of Data and Analytics

00:54:16.560 --> 00:54:17.360
